<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-07-17T04:15:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-07-17T04:15:00-05:00" n="222" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d222">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/4590½</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Memorandum of Telephone Conversation</hi><note n="83" xml:id="d222fn83">Between the Secretary of State in Paris
                                    and Mr. Ray Atherton, Counselor of Embassy in London, July 17,
                                    1931, 10:15 a.m.</note></head>
                            <dateline>
                                <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian" type="conversation-or-meeting-date" when="1931-07-17T10:15:00+01:00">July 17, 1931, 10:15
                                    a.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                            <p>Mr. Atherton said that the meeting at London had been definitely set
                                for 6 P.M. on Monday.<note n="84" xml:id="d222fn84">July 20.</note>
                                The Secretary told Atherton that it should be clearly understood in
                                London that Henderson had fully agreed to the suggestion that the
                                Germans come to Paris first and that everyone here in Paris felt
                                that this was desirable.</p>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>